  <h1>Synchronizing YouTube Videos with Your Own Workout</h1>

  <p>
    YouTube contains many videos that work well for cycling workouts. These include route videos, mountain pass rides,
    landscape footage, or complete tours filmed from the rider&rsquo;s perspective. But when such a video is played
    directly on YouTube, it is not connected to the workout itself. The video continues along its fixed timeline,
    regardless of how fast or slowly the rider is actually moving.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is exactly where synchronization comes in. The goal is to link the position in the video to a real or manually
    traced route so that playback no longer follows only a fixed video duration, but instead follows the rider&rsquo;s
    progress along the route.
  </p>

  <h2>Starting Point</h2>

  <p>
    A YouTube video initially provides only a timeline. A GPX file, by contrast, describes a route using spatial
    coordinates. The two data sources therefore contain different kinds of information:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>the video provides the visual representation of a ride</li>
    <li>the GPX file provides the geometric description of the route</li>
    <li>there is initially no direct mapping between the two</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Without that mapping, it is impossible to know which point in the video corresponds to which position on the route.
    That means neither the current video position can be derived from workout progress nor can playback be adjusted in a
    meaningful way.
  </p>

  <h2>Technical Approach</h2>

  <p>
    Synchronization is based on reference points between video time and route position. These reference points are used
    here as synchronization anchors. Each anchor describes a known mapping, for example:
  </p>

  <pre><code>00:00  -&gt;   0.0 km
05:30  -&gt;   3.2 km
12:10  -&gt;   8.7 km</code></pre>

  <p>
    The system interpolates between these points. This creates a mapping between time in the video and position on the
    route. That makes it possible to calculate, at any moment, where the video is on the route. Conversely, the current
    position on the route can also be used to determine which moment in the video should be shown.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Simple Global Scaling Is Not Enough</h2>

  <p>
    One obvious idea would be to map the full video duration to the full route length. In practice, however, that is not
    sufficient. Route videos often contain sections with different riding speeds, short stops, or other irregularities.
    GPX data is not always perfectly uniform or exact either.
  </p>

  <p>
    If only global scaling is used, drift appears over time. The video then runs visibly ahead of or behind the route.
    Local reference points are therefore necessary to keep the mapping stable enough along the route.
  </p>

  <h2>Behavior During the Workout</h2>

  <p>
    During the workout, a target position in the video is continuously calculated from the current route position. This
    leads to two typical mechanisms:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>for smaller deviations, the playback speed is adjusted</li>
    <li>for larger deviations, the video position is deliberately reset</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This creates a continuous follow-up behavior rather than a rigid coupling. The video can follow the actual workout
    without visibly jumping for every small difference.
  </p>

  <h2>Example</h2>

  <p>A typical example of suitable material is a route video on YouTube:</p>

  <p>
    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open YouTube video</a>
  </p>

  <p>
    When such a video is linked to a GPX file or a manually traced route, it stops being an ordinary video and becomes
    route-based playback whose progress depends on the workout.
  </p>

  <h2>Observations from the Implementation</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>even a few well-placed anchor points are often enough</li>
    <li>more anchor points do not automatically increase quality</li>
    <li>small deviations become visibly cumulative over longer distances</li>
    <li>what matters is not only mathematical accuracy, but also calm playback behavior</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Conclusion</h2>

  <p>
    YouTube already contains a large amount of material suitable for indoor cycling. What is normally missing is the
    technical connection between video playback and workout progress. By mapping video time to route position, that gap
    can be closed.
  </p>

  <p>
    The result is playback in which the video is no longer simply played, but instead follows the course of the workout.
  </p>
